Trap Calibrations

Goal: Figure out how fast a bead can move through solution in the trap.

How: In force_feedback.vi, trap a 1 micron bead in the right trap, go down near the surface, and rapidly move the stage a set distance.

Attempt #1 - 10 micron stage movement Set the ‘Stage X um’ slider to 0 - 10 and click back and forth. I used our previous step cal of 30nm/mV to convert raw signal to nm displacements.

Raw data:

I calculated the change in relative position datapoint to datapoint (i.e. if x1 = 1 and the x2 = 10 that is a change of 9nm) 

## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##       mean    sd   max   min
##      <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 0.000688  8.86  34.4 -36.0

Here is a trace with no stage movement - movement dictated by brownian motion:

Taking the relative change in position:

## # A tibble: 1 x 4
##        mean    sd   max   min
##       <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
## 1 -0.000313  9.16  35.2 -36.0

Conclusions: The trapped bead can move up to 36nm in 1 datapoint. At 5kHz, this is 36nm in 0.2 ms. Which is 180nm/ms -> 180,000nm/sec -> 180 microns/sec.
